<Layout title="About — Narrative Attraction Agency for Higher Education"
  description="701am is a narrative attraction agency for higher education. Built by a team that spent 20 years in education visibility — now helping institutions tell their story across press, AI, and social media.">
<div class="ph">
  <p class="ey">About 701am</p>
  <h1>We spent 20 years doing narrative attraction by hand. <span class="g">Now we do it for institutions.</span></h1>
  <p>After two decades building and operating education visibility properties that millions of prospective students used to compare programs, we started 701am to do for institutions what we used to do for ourselves — narrative attraction that compounds across press, AI, and social media.</p>
</div>

<article class="prose">
<span class="seg">Where we started</span>
<p class="lede">We've spent two decades on one question: when someone is choosing a school, how do they decide — and how do you make sure your program is in that decision?</p>
<p>We were part of the teams that built and operated a network of education properties — <strong>CollegeChoice.net</strong>, <strong>TheBestSchools.org</strong>, <strong>AffordableSchools.net</strong>, <strong>OnlineSchoolsCenter.com</strong>, <strong>CollegeValuesOnline.com</strong>, <strong>CollegeConsensus.com</strong>, and many more — that millions of prospective students used to compare programs. We understood exactly how applicants research, what makes a program credible, and how to put the right institutions in front of the right students at the moment they were deciding.</p>
<p>That's not adjacent experience. That's <em>the job</em>. We just spent twenty years doing it manually, site by site, before the technology existed to help institutions do it for themselves.</p>

<span class="seg">The ground moved</span>
<p>A few years ago, the behavior we'd built a career around started to change. Applicants stopped beginning with a Google search and a comparison site. They started asking an AI assistant — <em>"what's the best online MSW for working adults?"</em> — and taking the short, confident answer it gave them. They discovered programs through TikTok, Instagram, and YouTube, in channels that didn't exist a decade ago.</p>
<blockquote>The decision was forming somewhere most institutions couldn't see — or optimize for.</blockquote>
<p>We watched institutions that had spent years and fortunes on their visibility quietly disappear from the places applicants were looking. Not because their programs got worse — because the place the decision happened moved, and the old playbooks couldn't follow.</p>

<span class="seg">Why 701am exists</span>
<p>The signals that make a program credible haven't actually changed. Rankings. Real outcomes data. Coverage in publications people trust. Those still decide who gets shortlisted — it's just that <strong>an AI reads them now too</strong>, alongside the humans — and prospective students are discovering schools on TikTok, Instagram, and YouTube. The work that earns those signals is the same work we've done for two decades. It's just slow, manual, and expensive when done by a traditional agency — which is why most institutions only do it in bursts and then let it reset.</p>
<p>701am is the agency we wish had existed: a narrative attraction firm purpose-built for higher education, that earns coverage continuously across press, AI, and social media — so an institution's visibility compounds instead of resetting, and it shows up in the AI answer, the social feed, and the press, all at once.</p>
<blockquote>We're not a PR firm that discovered higher ed. We're education-visibility operators who spent two decades on this exact problem — now serving the institutions that need it.</blockquote>
</article>

